          <physDesc>
            <objectDesc>
              <supportDesc material="mixed">
                <support>
                  <p>non-European laid paper</p>
                </support>
                <extent>12 + 1 leaves : 221 x 142 (175 x 95) mm, bound to 230 x 145 mm</extent>
                <foliation>Modern foliation added in pencil, upper left recto; catchwords every verso, lower left.</foliation>
              </supportDesc>
              <layoutDesc>
                <layout>12 long lines; border-ruled.</layout>
              </layoutDesc>
            </objectDesc>
            <scriptDesc>
              <scriptNote>Naskh in black ink; fully vocalized.</scriptNote>
            </scriptDesc>
            <decoDesc>
              <decoNote>Polychrome (red, blue, pink, orange, black, green, yellow, white) and gold illuminated headpiece (f. 2v). Textblock border-rules in red, gold, black, blue; page opening frame-ruled in black. Rubrications in red with gold and blue highlights. Gold roundels with red and blue dots mark verse endings. Surah titles in red on gold background with polychrome edge decorations. Polychrome and gold medallions in the margins.</decoNote>
              <decoNote n="2r">Waqf statement</decoNote>
              <decoNote n="2v">Illuminated headpiece</decoNote>
              <decoNote n="6r">Medallion</decoNote>
              <decoNote n="10r">Illuminated chapter heading</decoNote>
            </decoDesc>
            <bindingDesc>
              <binding>
                <p>Reddish brown leather, blind stamped with central mandorla and six pendants, four on the vertical and two on the horizontal axis, lead ruled and tooled frame. Marbled paper pastedowns.</p>
              </binding>
            </bindingDesc>
          </physDesc>
          <history>
            <origin>
              <p>No date of copy, though the donation note is dated Rajab 1284 (October-November 1867) (f. 2r). Possibly copied in Iran.</p>
              <origDate>1750?-1867</origDate>
              <origPlace>Iran?</origPlace>
            </origin>
            <provenance>Gift of David Eugene Smith, 1931-1934.</provenance>
          </history>
